heard at the left sternal edge that varies with position and exertion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the expected response of the murmur to physical manoeuvres?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increases with isometric exercise, decreases with hand grip","Increases with standing and Valsalva","Increases with hand grip, decreases with Valsalva","Increases with squatting, decreases with standing","Increases with passive leg raise, decreases with standing"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy (HOCM), the severity of left ventricular outflow tract obstruction is dynamic and varies with loading conditions and contractility. Understanding these variations helps in both diagnosis and management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases with standing and Valsalva\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because both these manoeuvres reduce venous return to the heart. This decreases left ventricular volume, bringing the hypertrophied septum closer to the anterior mitral leaflet, thus worsening the obstruction and increasing the murmur intensity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases with squatting, decreases with standing\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Squatting increases venous return and afterload, which reduces the obstruction and therefore decreases the murmur. The opposite occurs with standing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases with hand grip, decreases with Valsalva\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Hand grip (isometric exercise) increases afterload which reduces obstruction. Valsalva increases obstruction as described above.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases with passive leg raise, decreases with standing\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Passive leg raise, like squatting, increases venous return which reduces obstruction. Standing reduces venous return and increases obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases with isometric exercise, decreases with hand grip\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as these are the same manoeuvre - both increase afterload and reduce obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese dynamic changes in murmur intensity form the basis of bedside diagnosis of HOCM and help differentiate it from other causes of left ventricular outflow tract obstruction. The principles can be remembered by understanding that anything that decreases preload (venous return) or increases contractility will worsen the obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dynamic left ventricular outflow tract obstruction in hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy worsens with increased contractility and reduced preload.","Physical examination findings in HOCM typically worsen with manoeuvres that decrease venous return or increase contractility.","The characteristic murmur of HOCM becomes louder with Valsalva and standing, and softer with squatting."],"references":["Basit H, Alahmadi MH, Rout P, et al. Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy. [Updated 2024 Jun 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430788/","Ommen, S. R., Mital, S., Burke, M. A., Day, S. M., Deswal, A., Elliott, P., Evanovich, L. L., Hung, J., Joglar, J. A., Kantor, P., Kimmelstiel, C., Kittleson, M., Link, M. S., Maron, M. S., Martinez, M. W., Miyake, C. Y., Schaff, H. V., Semsarian, C., \u0026 Sorajja, P. (2020). 2020 AHA/ACC Guideline for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Patients With Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy. Circulation, 142(25). https://doi.org/10.1161/cir.0000000000000937"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65174"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18862"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65174"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-16T09:46:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-16T09:47:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11595"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79877"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information